node.text:
This week, instead of sipping, we’re snacking. Contributing editor Sean Flynn (@travelingnewyorker) is back in Riviera Nayarit, Mexico at One&Only Mandarina (@oomandarina) cooking with Executive Chef Olivier Deboise (@olideboise). Chef’s Fire-Roasted Gratinated Oysters are sure to be a hit at your next summer party.
.
Ingredients:
½ dozen oysters
1 ½ oz butter
1 ½ oz aged goat cheddar
½ tsp shallots, diced
½ tsp Serrano chili, chopped
½ tsp epazote, julienned
Zest of 1 lemon
Zest of 1 lime 
.
Top each oyster with ¼ oz of butter and divide the chopped ingredients, lemon zest, and lime zest among the oysters. Top with grated aged goat cheddar. Grill over a medium to low flame for three to four minutes and brûlée for one and a half minutes. Serve hot.

node.title: These Fire-Roasted Oysters Are the Perfect Summer Appetizer

node.text: Next up on Sipping With, Sean (@travelingnewyorker) visits One&Only Mandarina (@oomandarina) in beautiful Riviera Nayarit, Mexico, where Mixologist Ivan Aguilar shows us how to make one of his favorite cocktails. Of course, no trip to Mexico is complete without tequila, so naturally, that’s our spirit of choice for this episode. In fact, Ivan shows us that tequila can be used to add a twist to cocktails that traditionally use other liquors. We hope you’ll follow along and sip with us at home. Cheers!

node.title: Calling All Tequila Lovers, This Cocktail Could Become Your New Favorite

Cheers!

node.title: Learn How One of the Best Hotels in NYC Makes Its Signature Margarita

node.text: In this new video series, Walk With T+L, we'll be taking you on some of the best walking tours across the globe. On this episode: the island of Amorgos, Greece. Luckily, there are more than 200 inhabited islands in Greece, meaning you can get all of the beauty and none the crowds on some of the lesser-known islands, like Amorgos. Come along! Tour by @_thebluewalk

node.text:
This week on Behind the Views: Henry Wu (@humminglion). Henry admits that when he bought his very first DSLR camera back in 2005, he had no clue what he was doing. Then, through reading photography books and plenty of trial and error, he slowly began to understand the basics, like exposure, composition, and post-processing. “One of the great things about photography is that it’s an ever-evolving craft that you can continuously hone and sharpen for the rest of your life,” he recently told T+L.
.
It wasn’t until a six-month trip to Southeast Asia in 2011 that Henry discovered how to combine travel, culture, and photography — and how much he loved it. “One of my favorite memories from that trip was when I was shooting at a remote village market in Vietnam. Amongst hundreds of boats carrying fresh noodles and produce, I captured a shot of one villager handing a basket of fruit to another boat,” he says. “I remember feeling lost in the moment and but equally present. I live for moments like that.”
.
Henry’s advice for aspiring travel photographers: “At first, you might find yourself emulating other photographers, which is great since it’s part of the learning process. But over time, it’s important to find your own voice and style to build your personal brand. Last but not least, have fun, never stop learning, and leave the camera at home every now and then.”
.
In Henry’s go-to camera bag you’ll find: a Nikon Z6II camera, Nikon Z 24-70mm lens, iPhone 12 Pro, DJI Mavic Air 2 drone, lens cloths, SD cards, and extra batteries.
.
All photos by @humminglion
